{"tool": "propose", "answer": "Synaptic pruning is the activity-dependent elimination and refinement of synapses that helps adolescent brain circuits become more efficient. During adolescence, this process is especially prominent in prefrontal and association cortices, regions involved in executive control, social cognition, emotion regulation, and reward learning. Because these same systems are still maturing, abnormal pruning may shift the balance between adaptive refinement and pathological loss of connectivity.\n\nIn schizophrenia, one influential hypothesis is that excessive or mistimed pruning in late adolescence and early adulthood contributes to the emergence of symptoms. Genetic findings implicating complement component 4, together with evidence that complement proteins and microglia tag and remove synapses, suggest a mechanism by which immune-related risk could lead to over-elimination of cortical synapses. This could help explain reduced cortical connectivity, cognitive impairment, and the typical timing of schizophrenia onset after puberty.\n\nFor depression, the relationship is more indirect but still important. Adolescence is a period when stress hormones, inflammation, sleep disruption, and social adversity can shape synaptic plasticity in prefrontal-limbic circuits. If pruning or synaptic remodeling is biased by chronic stress, the result may be weakened top-down regulation of amygdala and reward pathways, increasing vulnerability to persistent low mood, anhedonia, and impaired emotion regulation.\n\nOverall, adolescent pruning should be viewed as a sensitive developmental process rather than a simple cause of psychiatric illness. Normal pruning supports maturation, but genetic risk, immune signaling, stress exposure, and environmental context may alter its timing or extent. A useful research direction is to combine longitudinal imaging, inflammatory and genetic markers, and behavioral measures to identify when pruning trajectories become maladaptive